    <subfield code="s">10872</subfield>
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1335297/files/diurnaltheta.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00007 Due to the diurnal motion of the Earth different angles $\Theta$ in galactic coordinates are sampled as the earth rotates. The angle $\Theta$ scanned by the direction of observation is shown for various inclinations $\tilde{\delta}$. We see that, for negative inclinations, the angle $\Theta$ can take values near $\pi$, i.e. opposite to the direction of the sun's velocity, where the rate attains its maximum.For an explanation of the curves see Fig. \ref{fig:diurnal}</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="s">12069</subfield>
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1335297/files/AxionDifMod.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00002 The angular average $\rho_a/m_a\prec{\vec \upsilon} .{\hat n}\succ$, essentially the corresponding axion flux, in units of $(\rho_a/m_a)\upsilon_0$, is shown as a function of its velocity in units of $\upsilon_0$ for the values of $\Theta=0,\pi/4,\pi/2,5 \pi/8,3\pi/4,7\pi/8$ and $\pi$ increasing upwards. We note the large asymmetry. The most favored direction is opposite to the sun's velocity.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
